         "id": "SECTION_local_content",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Earth: A \"Living\" Planet</h3>When discussing maps, it is essential to consider geological time, as continents have not always existed in their present form. Besides the continental landmasses, we must also account for tectonic plate movements, which play a major role in the formation and transformation of visible land structures",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "021534bf-9945-43c6-ae30-7d1bcd43aecd",
                     "text": "Windley, Brian Frederick",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "04",
                        "day": "05"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2440434d-29ba-4475-814e-a15eec9e63c2",
                     "text": "Andel, Tjeerd H. van and Murphy, J. Brendan",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "10"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "Before continents settled into their current configuration, Earth went through periods dominated by supercontinents. One example is Gondwana, a massive landmass that included what are now South America (<i>Abya Yala</i>), Africa, India, Australia, and Antarctica. This supercontinent encompassed the region from which our species would later emerge: Africa",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "59c0b962-d032-4b6c-9498-2341e089510b",
                     "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "750e84b5-9330-4f99-92b0-72469a6a64f4",
                     "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d8dee061-0e72-4ca5-bfe3-bcfa3c42b070",
                     "text": "Redacción National Geographic",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "07",
                        "day": "08"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9b86417a-a5bf-4211-bc42-ee8a1d3739c0",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "14"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "06780f2e-073c-4da7-869e-945ecd275316",
                     "text": "Stampfli, G. M., et al.",
                     "page": " pp. 2 - 10",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "Over millions of years, Gondwana joined with other landmasses to form the supercontinent Pangea. Eventually, Pangea began to break apart due to tectonic plate movement, a process that, according to the most widely accepted geological models, led to the formation of the continents as we know them today",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8634e87f-9ea9-4fdd-9a26-ae3b33e17af1",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "07",
                        "day": "23"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "06780f2e-073c-4da7-869e-945ecd275316",
